[3]
Date: Thu 18 Apr 2013
Source: Focus Taiwan News Channel [edited]
http://focustaiwan.tw/news/aedu/201304170035.aspx


The deadly H7N9 avian flu virus can be traced to 3 bird species: a brambling from Beijing, fowl in the Yangtze River Delta, and a wild bird from the Korean peninsula, according to a Chinese scientist.

Xue Yu, a professor at Huazhong University of Science and Technology in Wuhan in central China, said his research team reached the conclusion about the 3 bird species after completing an analysis of the H7N9 virus's genetic makeup.

Xue said his research team obtained genetic sequence data from 4 H7N9 virus samples for an analytical study, according to the Wuhan-based Changjiang Daily.

The team compared the genetic sequences of the 4 samples with those of 110 000 samples in an influenza virus sequence database in the United States.

"The comparative analysis has allowed us to reach an initial conclusion on the H7N9 virus's evolution," Xue was quoted as saying in the news report.

Sometime before last November [2012], he said, the H9N2 carried by a brambling from Beijing interacted with the H7N3 virus carried by fowl in the Yangtze River Delta.

"Each of these 2 species provided 3 genes to form part of the H7N9 virus. These 6 genes alone, however, would not sicken humans," Xue said.

Roughly at the same time, a duck in Zhejiang Province in the Yangtze River Delta provided hemagglutinin (HA) to turn the above-mentioned genes into H7N2/N3, Xue said.

"This was a critical step for the virus to get the key to infect or invade human or animal cells," Xue said.

In the 3rd stage that took place around 19 Feb 2013, a wild bird from the Korean peninsula brought in the most important element, neuraminidase (NA), to complete the H7N9 virus's genetic makeup of 8 genes, Xue said.

"NA allows the virus to spread freely in its host," Xue said.

He said China has put the genetic sequences of the 4 H7N9 genes into an international database for scientists around the world to analyze and study.

"When we get more samples, we will be able to better understand the evolution of the H7N9 virus," Xue said, adding that the conclusions may be adjusted or even changed fundamentally.

[Byline: Chiu Kuo-chaing and Sofia Wu]

